# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-vitals-monitoring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] The Performance API is a group of standards used to measure the performance of web applications.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] To ensure web applications are fast, it's important to measure and analyze various performance metrics.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] The Performance API provides important built-in metrics and the ability to add your own measurements to the browser's performance timeline.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] The performance timeline contains high precision timestamps and can be displayed in developer tools.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] You can also send its data to analytics end points to record performance metrics over time.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] Each performance metric is represented by a single `PerformanceEntry`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] A performance entry has a `name`, a `duration`, a `startTime`, and a `type`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] All performance metrics extend the `PerformanceEntry` interface and qualify it further.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] Most of the performance entries are recorded for you without you having to do anything, and are then accessible either through `Performance.getEntries()` or (preferably) through `PerformanceObserver`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] For example, `PerformanceEventTiming` entries are recorded for events that take longer than a set threshold.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] But the Performance API also enables you to define and record your own custom events, using the `PerformanceMark` and `PerformanceMeasure` interfaces.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] The main `Performance` interface is available in both `Window` and `Worker` global scopes, and enables you to add custom performance entries, to clear performance entries, and to retrieve performance entries.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] The `PerformanceObserver` interface enables you to listen for various types of performance entry as they are recorded.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] For more conceptual information, see the Performance API guides below.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] A read-only map returned by `performance.eventCounts` containing the number of events which have been dispatched per event type.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] Measures the render time of the largest image or text block visible within the viewport, recorded from when the page first begins to load.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] Provides insights into the layout stability of web pages based on movements of the elements on the page.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] Provides debugging information about elements which have shifted.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] Represents a single reason why a navigated page was blocked from using the back/forward cache (bfcache).
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] Provides report data containing reasons why the current document was blocked from using the back/forward cache (bfcache) on navigation.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] Main interface to access performance measurements.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] Available to window and worker contexts using `Window.performance` or `WorkerGlobalScope.performance`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-api] Measures rendering timestamps of specific elements.
