[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] The **`mark()`** method creates a named `PerformanceMark` object representing a high resolution timestamp marker in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] A string representing the name of the mark.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] Must not be the same name as one of the properties of the deprecated `PerformanceTiming` interface.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] An object for specifying a timestamp and additional metadata for the mark.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] Arbitrary metadata to include in the mark.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] Some browsers have use a structured `devtools` object within the `detail` object as part of an Extensibility API that surfaces these in custom tracks in performance traces.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] See the Chrome's Extensibility API documentation for more information.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] `DOMHighResTimeStamp` to use as the mark time.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] The `PerformanceMark` entry that was created.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] The following example uses `mark()` to create named `PerformanceMark` entries.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] You can create several marks with the same name.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] You can also assign them, to have a reference to the `PerformanceMark` object that has been created.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] The performance mark is configurable using the `markOptions` object where you can put additional information in the `detail` property, which can be of any type.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] The default timestamp of the `mark()` method is `performance.now()`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] You can set it to a different time using the `startTime` option in `markOptions`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-mark] Note in order to maintain backwards compatibility, names that are part of the deprecated `PerformanceTiming` interface can't be used.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] The **`measure()`** method creates a named `PerformanceMeasure` object representing a time measurement between two marks in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] When measuring between two marks, there is a *start mark* and *end mark*, respectively.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] The named timestamp is referred to as a *measure*.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] If only `measureName` is specified, the start timestamp is set to zero, and the end timestamp (which is used to calculate the duration) is the value that would be returned by `Performance.now()`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] You can use strings to identify `PerformanceMark` objects as start and end marks.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] To only provide an `endMark`, you need to provide an empty `measureOptions` object: `performance.measure("myMeasure", {}, "myEndMarker")`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] A string representing the name of the measure.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] An object that may contain measure options.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] Arbitrary metadata to be included in the measure.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] String with a value of `track-entry` (for defining a new track) or `marker` (for defining an entry in a track).
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] Timestamp (`DOMHighResTimeStamp`) to be used as the start time, or string that names a `PerformanceMark` to use for the start time.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] If this is a string naming a `PerformanceMark`, then it is defined in the same way as `startMark`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] Duration (in milliseconds) between the start and end mark times.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] If omitted, this defaults to `performance.now()`; the time that has elapsed since the context was created.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] If provided, you must also specify either `start` or `end` but not both.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] Timestamp (`DOMHighResTimeStamp`) to be used as the end time, or string that names a `PerformanceMark` to use for the end time.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] If this is a string naming a `PerformanceMark`, then it is defined in the same way as `endMark`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] A string naming a `PerformanceMark` in the performance timeline.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] The `PerformanceEntry.startTime` property of this mark will be used for calculating the measure.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] If you want to pass this argument, you must also pass either `startMark` or an empty `measureOptions` object.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] The `PerformanceMeasure` entry that was created.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] The `measureOptions.detail` value is non-`null` and cannot be serialized using the HTML "StructuredSerialize" algorithm.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] The `measureOptions.detail` value is non-`null` and memory cannot be allocated during serialization using the HTML "StructuredSerialize" algorithm.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] Given two of your own markers `"login-started"` and `"login-finished"`, you can create a measurement called `"login-duration"` as shown in the following example.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] The returned `PerformanceMeasure` object will then provide a `duration` property to tell you the elapsed time between the two markers.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] To do more advanced measurements, you can pass a `measureOptions` parameter.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] For example, you can use the `event.timeStamp` property from a `click` event as the start time.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] You can use the `details` property to provide additional information of any type.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performance-measure] Maybe you want to record which HTML element was clicked, for example.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] The **`PerformanceEntry`** object encapsulates a single performance metric that is part of the browser's performance timeline.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] The Performance API offers built-in metrics which are specialized subclasses of `PerformanceEntry`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] This includes entries for resource loading, event timing, and more.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] A performance entry can also be created by calling the `Performance.mark()` or `Performance.measure()` methods at an explicit point in an application.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] This allows you to add your own metrics to the performance timeline.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] A string representing the name for a performance entry.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] A string representing the type of performance metric.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] For example, `"mark"` when `PerformanceMark` is used.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the starting time for the performance metric.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the duration of the performance entry.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] Returns a JSON representation of the `PerformanceEntry` object.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] The following example creates `PerformanceEntry` objects that are of the types `PerformanceMark` and `PerformanceMeasure`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performanceentry] The `PerformanceMark` and `PerformanceMeasure` subclasses inherit the `duration`, `entryType`, `name`, and `startTime` properties from `PerformanceEntry` and set them to their appropriate values.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] It’s been available across browsers since April 2021.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] The **`PerformancePaintTiming`** interface provides timing information about "paint" (also called "render") operations during web page construction.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] "Paint" refers to conversion of the render tree to on-screen pixels.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] The data this API provides helps you minimize the time that users have to wait before they can see the site's content start to appear.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] Decreasing the time until these key paint moments make sites feel more responsive, performant, and engaging for your users.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] Like other Performance APIs, this API extends `PerformanceEntry`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] Returns the `timestamp` when the rendering phase ended and the paint phase started.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] Returns the `timestamp` when the painted pixels were actually drawn on the screen.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] Returns either `"first-paint"` or `"first-contentful-paint"`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] Returns the `timestamp` when the paint occurred.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] Returns a JSON representation of the `PerformancePaintTiming` object.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] Example using a `PerformanceObserver`, which notifies of new `paint` performance entries as they are recorded in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] Use the `buffered` option to access entries from before the observer creation.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] The `paintTime` and `presentationTime` properties enable you to retrieve specific timings for the paint phase starting and the painted pixels being drawn on the screen.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] The `paintTime` is broadly interoperable, whereas the `presentationTime` is implementation-dependent.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] This example builds on the earlier `Performance.getEntriesByType()` example, showing how to check for `paintTime` and `presentationTime` support and retrieve those values if they are available.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/performancepainttiming] In non-supporting browsers, the code retrieves the `loadTime`.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Faster website download speeds have been shown to increase visitor retention and loyalty and user satisfaction, especially for users with slow internet connections and those on mobile devices.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Web performance also leads to less data travelling across the web, which in turn lowers a website's power consumption and environmental impact.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Some aspects which can affect the speed of page load include browser/server cache, image optimization, and encryption (for example SSL), which can affect the time it takes for pages to render.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] The performance of the web page can be improved through techniques such as multi-layered cache, light weight design of presentation layer components and asynchronous communication with server side components.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] In the first decade or so of the web's existence, web performance improvement was focused mainly on optimizing website code and pushing hardware limitations.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] According to the 2002 book *Web Performance Tuning* by Patrick Killelea, some of the early techniques used were to use simple servlets or CGI, increase server memory, and look for packet loss and retransmission.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Although these principles now comprise much of the optimized foundation of internet applications, they differ from current optimization theory in that there was much less of an attempt to improve the browser display speed.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Steve Souders coined the term "web performance optimization" in 2004.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] At that time Souders made several predictions regarding the impact that WPO as an "emerging industry" would bring to the web, such as websites being fast by default, consolidation, web standards for performance, environmental impacts of optimization, and speed as a differentiator.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] One major point that Souders made in 2007 is that at least 80% of the time that it takes to download and view a website is controlled by the front-end structure.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] This lag time can be decreased through awareness of typical browser behavior, as well as of how HTTP works.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Web performance optimization improves user experience (UX) when visiting a website and therefore is highly desired by web designers and web developers.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] They employ several techniques that streamline web optimization tasks to decrease web page load times.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] This process is known as front end optimization (FEO) or content optimization.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] In addition to the techniques listed below, the use of a content delivery network—a group of proxy servers spread across various locations around the globe—is an efficient delivery system that chooses a server for a specific user based on network proximity.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Typically the server with the quickest response time is selected.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Web browsers open separate Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) connections for each Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) request submitted when downloading a web page.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] These requests total the number of page elements required for download.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] However, a browser is limited to opening only a certain number of simultaneous connections to a single host.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] To prevent bottlenecks, the number of individual page elements are reduced using resource consolidation whereby smaller files (such as images) are bundled together into one file.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] This reduces HTTP requests and the number of "round trips" required to load a web page.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Web pages are constructed from code files such JavaScript and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML).
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] As web pages grow in complexity, so do their code files and subsequently their load times.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] File compression can reduce code files by about 40 percent, thereby improving site responsiveness.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Web Caching Optimization reduces server load, bandwidth usage and latency.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] CDNs use dedicated web caching software to store copies of documents passing through their system.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Many website platforms, such as SiteGround, IONOS, Wix, and Hostinger, rely on global CDNs and caching technologies to deliver faster page loads across different geographical regions.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Subsequent requests from the cache may be fulfilled should certain conditions apply.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Web caches are located on either the client side (forward position) or web-server side (reverse position) of a CDN.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Web browsers are also able to store content for re-use through the HTTP cache or web cache.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Requests web browsers make are typically routed to the HTTP cache to validate if a cached response may be used to fulfill a request.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] If such a match is made, the response is fulfilled from the cache.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] This can be helpful for reducing network latency and costs associated with data-transfer.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] The HTTP cache is configured using request and response headers.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Code minification distinguishes discrepancies between codes written by web developers and how network elements interpret code.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Minification removes comments and extra spaces as well as crunch variable names in order to minimize code, decreasing files sizes by as much as 60%.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] In addition to caching and compression, lossy compression techniques (similar to those used with audio files) remove non-essential header information and lower original image quality on many high resolution images.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] These changes, such as pixel complexity or color gradations, are transparent to the end-user and do not noticeably affect perception of the image.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Another technique is the replacement of raster graphics with resolution-independent vector graphics.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Vector substitution is best suited for simple geometric images.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Lazy loading of images and video reduces initial page load time, initial page weight, and system resource usage, all of which have positive impacts on website performance.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] It is used to defer initialization of an object right until the point at which it is needed.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] The browser loads the images in a page or post when they are needed such as when the user scrolls down the page and not all images at once, which is the default behavior, and naturally, takes more time.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Since web browsers use multiple TCP connections for parallel user requests, congestion and browser monopolization of network resources may occur.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Because HTTP/1 requests come with associated overhead, web performance is impacted by limited bandwidth and increased usage.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Instead of a website's hosting server, CDNs are used in tandem with HTTP/2 in order to better serve the end-user with web resources such as images, JavaScript files and Cascading Style Sheet (CSS) files since a CDN's location is usually in closer proximity to the end-user.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] In recent years, several metrics have been introduced that help developers measure various aspects of the performance of their websites.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Modules to measure metrics such as TTFB, FCP, LCP, FP etc are provided with major frontend JavaScript libraries such as React, NuxtJS and Vue.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] Google publishes a library, the core-web-vitals library that allows for easy measurement of these metrics in frontend applications.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] In addition to this, Google also provides the Lighthouse, a Chrome dev-tools component and PageSpeed Insight a site that allows developers to measure and compare the performance of their website with Google's recommended minimums and maximums.
[src:web-vitals-monitoring/web-performance] In addition to this, tools such as the Network Monitor by Mozilla Firefox help provide insight into network-level slowdowns that might occur during transmission of data.
